    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/ai",
      "category": "ai",
      "title": "The Future of the Con Is Already Here, It's Just Not Evenly Distributed",
      "url": "http://manishearth.github.io/blog/2026/06/17/the-future-of-the-con-is-already-here/",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/5majlp",
      "score": 84,
      "comments": 39,
      "author": "Manishearth",
      "published": "2026-06-18T16:25:48Z",
      "bullets": [
        "LLMs and generative AI automate hyper-personalized social engineering, scaling high-conviction spear-phishing campaigns at near-zero marginal cost.",
        "ElevenLabs-style voice cloning and deepfakes bypass traditional audio/video biometrics, escalating synthetic identity fraud and social engineering tactics.",
        "Defense must shift from AI-detection tools to cryptographic verification, WebAuthn hardware tokens, and zero-trust identity frameworks to mitigate synthetic fraud."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/programming",
      "category": "engineering",
      "title": "cl-bbs: the schemeBBS-like textboard rewritten in Common Lisp",
      "url": "https://github.com/ryukinix/cl-bbs",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/wgpa6x",
      "score": 4,
      "comments": 2,
      "author": "lerax",
      "published": "2026-06-21T07:19:03Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Migrating from MIT Scheme to Common Lisp allows `cl-bbs` to leverage a broader library ecosystem for scaling application features.",
        "New feature additions over SchemeBBS include persistent user preferences, image URL previews, an admin moderation page, and integrated search.",
        "The project preserves an authless, privacy-centric textboard model, avoiding complex cryptographic overhead for simple, lightweight deployments."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/security",
      "category": "security",
      "title": "Forward to Hell? On Misusing Transparent DNS Forwarders For Amplification Attacks",
      "url": "https://labs.ripe.net/author/mkoch/forward-to-hell-on-misusing-transparent-dns-forwarders-for-amplification-attacks/",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/ozr1zf",
      "score": 3,
      "comments": 0,
      "author": "jaguar",
      "published": "2026-06-21T08:24:37Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Transparent DNS forwarders bypass standard resolver protections, enabling attackers to exploit anycast resolver infrastructure for reflective DDoS amplification.",
        "This technique scales reflective DDoS attacks globally by hiding malicious request origins behind trusted public anycast DNS networks.",
        "Security teams must secure internal DNS forwarders, disable open recursive queries, and deploy response rate limiting to prevent exploitation."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/devops",
      "category": "devops",
      "title": "I am dreading our LLM-written incident report future",
      "url": "https://surfingcomplexity.blog/2026/06/19/i-am-dreading-our-llm-written-incident-report-future/",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/ysxvko",
      "score": 38,
      "comments": 14,
      "author": "azhenley",
      "published": "2026-06-20T00:51:33Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Automating incident postmortems with LLMs risks turning blameless RCAs into compliance-driven, sanitized paperwork that obscures actual systemic engineering failures.",
        "LLMs lack deep system context, risking hallucinated root causes in complex cloud environments while omitting critical, non-technical human factors.",
        "The manual process of writing RCAs builds engineering troubleshooting skills and institutional memory, which AI-generated summaries ultimately erode."
      ]
    },
